Till now, we’ve used arithmetic and increment/decrement operators — now we'll explore comparison operators like `==`, `!=`, `>`, `=`, and `

int main() {
    int num1 = 10;         // Integer value
    int num2 = 10;         // Another integer value
    double price1 = 5.99;  // Double value
    double price2 = 5.99;  // Another double value
    float a = 7.5f;        // Float value
    int b = 7;             // Integer value

    // Comparing integers
    printf("Comparing integers: %d\n", num1 == num2);      // Outputs: 1 (true)

    // Comparing floating-point numbers
    printf("Comparing doubles: %d\n", price1 == price2);   // Outputs: 1 (true)

    // Comparing float and int
    printf("Comparing float and int: %d\n", a == b);       // Outputs: 0 (false)

    return 0;
}
```

**Note:** Be cautious when comparing floating-point numbers (like `float` or `double`). Due to precision limitations, two values that appear equal may not always return `true`.

